-- 
-- Compound types are represented as separate 1:1 tables and enforces via
-- a combination of the use of both UNIQUE on columns that reference tables
-- representing Compound types and corresponding FK column constraint
-- definitions to those tables.
-- 
-- Though Compounds do not have an "mRID" and do not inherantly represent
-- persistent objects in the CIM (i.e. are inherited from IdentifiedObject)
-- they are here given a unique identifier "id" that is distinct from "mRID"
-- and used for persistence purposes.
-- 
-- Tables that represent Compound types in the CIM are not normalized for
-- the following reasons:
-- 
--   Normalization, particularly to 3NF, typically requires:
--     No repeating groups.
--     No partial or transitive dependencies.
--     Every non-key attribute must depend only on the whole key.
--     
--   But compound classes in the CIM domain:
--     Do not have surrogate or natural primary keys derived from business rules.
--     Are logically value objects: any change to any attribute means the value is distinct.
--     Have implicit semantic atomicity — they’re treated as indivisible chunks.
--     
